00:00:43.950 --> 00:00:48.661
MALE SPEAKER: So let's go back
to the beginning of the story.

00:00:48.661 --> 00:00:50.452
Your grandmother was
an inspiration to you.

00:00:50.452 --> 00:00:52.080
You talk about her quite often.

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:55.785
Was she the reason you got
into food to begin with?

00:00:55.785 --> 00:00:59.590
ADAM SOBEL: Well, I grew up
in a house with a lot of food.

00:00:59.590 --> 00:01:06.500
My mom is a literary agent
primarily for cookbook authors.

00:01:06.500 --> 00:01:09.730
So there were always people
testing recipes in our home

00:01:09.730 --> 00:01:14.140
and even doing photo shoots for
their cookbooks in our home.

00:01:14.140 --> 00:01:17.870
And I definitely
started learning cooking

00:01:17.870 --> 00:01:20.830
from my mom and
grandma, but really

00:01:20.830 --> 00:01:24.220
what got me into preparing
food professionally

00:01:24.220 --> 00:01:27.720
was when I met and fell
in love with the woman who

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:31.040
would become my wife, and
who I've had kids with,

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:32.770
in my late teens.

00:01:32.770 --> 00:01:35.170
And when I met
her, she was really

00:01:35.170 --> 00:01:38.030
one of the first vegan
people I'd gotten close with,

00:01:38.030 --> 00:01:41.790
but ate this diet of like
French fries, and canned soup,

00:01:41.790 --> 00:01:46.540
and the worst devoid of
nutrition kind of food.

00:01:46.540 --> 00:01:49.910
And I wasn't vegan
or vegetarian,

00:01:49.910 --> 00:01:53.800
but I really agreed
with the ethics

00:01:53.800 --> 00:01:56.980
behind her decision to eat
that way and live that way.

00:01:56.980 --> 00:01:59.500
And I really wanted to learn
how to make yummy food so

00:01:59.500 --> 00:02:02.870
that I can make great
things for all the time.

00:02:02.870 --> 00:02:06.160
And I started just going to
Barnes &amp; Noble's and trying

00:02:06.160 --> 00:02:09.669
to copy recipes out of
books and veganize things.

00:02:09.669 --> 00:02:12.810
And I started working at
restaurants really just

00:02:12.810 --> 00:02:18.020
to start picking up more
tricks to play around with.

00:02:18.020 --> 00:02:20.800
And then working
in restaurants, I

00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:24.280
myself became vegetarian
and then vegan.

00:02:24.280 --> 00:02:26.480
People would come
into the restaurants,

00:02:26.480 --> 00:02:30.410
trying to veganize
things or vegetarian

00:02:30.410 --> 00:02:32.180
things that were on the menu.

00:02:32.180 --> 00:02:35.250
And the other cooks
would scoff about it

00:02:35.250 --> 00:02:37.080
and give them a hard time.

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:40.440
And I kept finding myself
standing up for these people

00:02:40.440 --> 00:02:42.690
because I agreed with
the ethics behind it.

00:02:42.690 --> 00:02:44.950
And eventually,
somebody was like why

00:02:44.950 --> 00:02:47.210
aren't you vegetarian yet?

00:02:47.210 --> 00:02:50.180
And at that point, I
had no excuses left.

00:02:50.180 --> 00:02:53.650
And I was like, yeah,
you're probably right.

00:02:53.650 --> 00:02:57.030
And then I got really,
really into it.

00:02:57.030 --> 00:03:00.950
MALE SPEAKER: OK, so you start
cooking professionally then

00:03:00.950 --> 00:03:02.340
to learn how to cook.

00:03:02.340 --> 00:03:04.640
You figured might as
well get paid for it.

00:03:04.640 --> 00:03:09.490
I waited tables for
a few weeks terribly.

00:03:09.490 --> 00:03:14.300
So I know the restaurant
business is a difficult life.

00:03:14.300 --> 00:03:17.630
Did you know going into it
how challenging it would be?

00:03:17.630 --> 00:03:18.230
The hours?

00:03:18.230 --> 00:03:19.530
That sort of thing, or?

00:03:19.530 --> 00:03:20.488
ADAM SOBEL: Well, yeah.

00:03:20.488 --> 00:03:23.410
I mean, my first
restaurant gig was

00:03:23.410 --> 00:03:28.320
at a restaurant on the
Upper West Side West,

00:03:28.320 --> 00:03:30.880
which is one of Tom
Valenti's restaurants.

00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:33.400
And I was working
like six days a week,

00:03:33.400 --> 00:03:36.780
and I was baking cakes
for people on the side.

00:03:36.780 --> 00:03:40.200
And I would have to get on
this 4:00 in the morning bus

00:03:40.200 --> 00:03:42.780
from New Jersey,
where I was living,

00:03:42.780 --> 00:03:46.140
and drop off cakes I was
delivering on my way to work.

00:03:46.140 --> 00:03:48.930
And I worked this
horrendous, long day,

00:03:48.930 --> 00:03:52.580
and I would get like 2/3
of my sleep on the bus

00:03:52.580 --> 00:03:54.430
to and from the city.

00:03:54.430 --> 00:03:56.620
And it was the worst paying job.

00:03:56.620 --> 00:04:01.380
I probably wasn't getting even
paid minimum wage or something.

00:04:01.380 --> 00:04:03.810
But for me, that was
always way more attractive

00:04:03.810 --> 00:04:06.420
than paying to go
to culinary school.

00:04:06.420 --> 00:04:08.170
I always really
hated school myself.

00:04:08.170 --> 00:04:13.110
And now my kids, we
homeschool our kids.

00:04:13.110 --> 00:04:15.370
Because it's just not a
fun way for me to learn.

00:04:15.370 --> 00:04:18.350
I'd rather get paid very
little and work long days

00:04:18.350 --> 00:04:19.170
to learn that way.

00:04:19.170 --> 00:04:21.050
It's more fun for me.

00:04:21.050 --> 00:04:24.564
MALE SPEAKER: So you
were in the middle

00:04:24.564 --> 00:04:25.980
of the professional
cooking world.

00:04:25.980 --> 00:04:28.080
You were a talented chef.

00:04:28.080 --> 00:04:30.500
So maybe it's easier
for you to become vegan

00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:32.250
because you can prepare
food for yourself.

00:04:32.250 --> 00:04:34.650
I know a lot of people say,
oh, I could never be a vegan.

00:04:34.650 --> 00:04:37.160
I could never be a vegetarian.

00:04:37.160 --> 00:04:39.304
What do you say to people
that feel that way?

00:04:39.304 --> 00:04:40.720
ADAM SOBEL: Well,
I mean certainly

00:04:40.720 --> 00:04:45.860
when I chose to become a
vegetarian and then vegan,

00:04:45.860 --> 00:04:49.060
I wasn't a talented
chef at that point.

00:04:49.060 --> 00:04:51.470
I made plenty of
things that sucked.

00:04:51.470 --> 00:04:54.870
And to be honest, I still
throw out a terrible meal

00:04:54.870 --> 00:04:55.760
every once in awhile.

00:04:55.760 --> 00:04:57.720
It happens.

00:04:57.720 --> 00:05:00.100
That's part of trying to
get great at something.

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:02.550
You have to be willing
to fail at it miserably

00:05:02.550 --> 00:05:05.070
for years and years.

00:05:05.070 --> 00:05:08.950
But for me, the reasons
for my becoming vegan

00:05:08.950 --> 00:05:11.200
were always very
ethically based.

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:13.650
I think the people
who struggle with it

00:05:13.650 --> 00:05:16.850
are choosing to be vegan
maybe for health reasons

00:05:16.850 --> 00:05:21.370
or some other dietary concern.

00:05:21.370 --> 00:05:24.890
For me, I became really
aware of the suffering

00:05:24.890 --> 00:05:29.250
that animals endured to be part
of the food production system.

00:05:29.250 --> 00:05:34.160
And it just didn't feel like
it was worth it anymore.

00:05:37.370 --> 00:05:41.040
I hesitated becoming vegan
for quite awhile feeling

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:45.730
like it would be
encroaching upon my freedom

00:05:45.730 --> 00:05:47.915
to live however I wanted.

00:05:47.915 --> 00:05:49.850
And it's really not the case.

00:05:49.850 --> 00:05:53.430
Once I became very aware
of how animals are treated

00:05:53.430 --> 00:05:55.200
and what they have
to go through-- I

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:58.550
could still eat
animals if I wanted.

00:05:58.550 --> 00:06:00.110
I'm perfectly free to do that.

00:06:00.110 --> 00:06:03.670
I just don't want to
harm creatures anymore.

00:06:03.670 --> 00:06:07.760
So that's made it very
easy to never look back.

00:06:07.760 --> 00:06:10.080
MALE SPEAKER: I see.

00:06:10.080 --> 00:06:12.200
So you weren't a talented
chef when you started,

00:06:12.200 --> 00:06:12.790
you're saying?

00:06:12.790 --> 00:06:13.498
ADAM SOBEL: Yeah.

00:06:13.498 --> 00:06:14.200
No, I sucked.

00:06:14.200 --> 00:06:18.550
MALE SPEAKER: But I think the
lines of the Cinnamon Snail

00:06:18.550 --> 00:06:21.570
tell a different story
at least these days.

00:06:21.570 --> 00:06:23.930
So as a talented
chef who now has

00:06:23.930 --> 00:06:26.297
experience in the food
industry, when you're not

00:06:26.297 --> 00:06:27.880
eating the food that
you or your staff

00:06:27.880 --> 00:06:30.260
is cooking, what are your
favorite vegan meals?

00:06:30.260 --> 00:06:33.050
Maybe around the city, or
around the country, or world?

00:06:33.050 --> 00:06:37.240
ADAM SOBEL: Yeah, I mean,
what really attracts

00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:43.270
me the most in people's
cooking is really

00:06:43.270 --> 00:06:46.490
kind of feeling the love
that they've put in it.

00:06:46.490 --> 00:06:48.300
Not to sound really
cliche about it,

00:06:48.300 --> 00:06:53.130
but I think it's really evident
in some people's cooking style.

00:06:53.130 --> 00:06:55.680
Somebody makes
you a family meal,

00:06:55.680 --> 00:06:57.709
and it's their
grandmother's recipe,

00:06:57.709 --> 00:06:59.500
and they're making it
feel like they really

00:06:59.500 --> 00:07:02.840
care about you--
you just feel such

00:07:02.840 --> 00:07:04.610
a different energy in the food.

00:07:04.610 --> 00:07:08.270
And for me, it almost
becomes immaterial

00:07:08.270 --> 00:07:10.320
what the actual food is.

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:12.110
It's really like
you're being sustained

00:07:12.110 --> 00:07:14.250
by their nurturing energy.

00:07:14.250 --> 00:07:18.547
I think there's really very
few restaurants in the city

00:07:18.547 --> 00:07:19.630
that you can feel that at.

00:07:19.630 --> 00:07:23.050
Actually, one of my
favorites that was like that

00:07:23.050 --> 00:07:25.920
just closed like last week.

00:07:25.920 --> 00:07:28.500
It was the Lan
Vegetarian Restaurant

00:07:28.500 --> 00:07:33.650
on Sixth street, which was a
Vietnamese family run business.

00:07:33.650 --> 00:07:36.170
You could hear the mom and
dad in the kitchen listening

00:07:36.170 --> 00:07:40.540
to Buddhist hymns on loop,
and the son was their waiter.

00:07:40.540 --> 00:07:44.230
And it was a really sweet place,
and you felt like you were just

00:07:44.230 --> 00:07:45.790
eating in their home.

00:07:45.790 --> 00:07:48.160
So I mean, traveling
around, that's what

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:52.630
I gravitate towards when
I travel in India or Asia.

00:07:52.630 --> 00:07:54.880
Eating street food
made by somebody

00:07:54.880 --> 00:07:56.760
who really cares about
what they're doing,

00:07:56.760 --> 00:08:00.850
that's more exciting to me than
eating at the fanciest, most

00:08:00.850 --> 00:08:02.957
refined kind of restaurant.

00:08:02.957 --> 00:08:03.790
MALE SPEAKER: I see.

00:08:03.790 --> 00:08:05.060
So food with love.

00:08:05.060 --> 00:08:09.700
And you said you got
into the vegan cooking

00:08:09.700 --> 00:08:15.430
to help rescue your future wife
from french fry and canned soup

00:08:15.430 --> 00:08:17.010
vegetarianism.

00:08:17.010 --> 00:08:19.350
But we all have these
guilty food pleasures.

00:08:19.350 --> 00:08:21.460
What would you say yours is?

00:08:21.460 --> 00:08:24.218
ADAM SOBEL: Yeah, I'll
fuck up some fried food.

00:08:24.218 --> 00:08:26.510
No question about it.

00:08:26.510 --> 00:08:29.500
And I really try not to eat that
way regularly because I also

00:08:29.500 --> 00:08:30.900
practice a lot of yoga.

00:08:30.900 --> 00:08:34.429
And I also really
want-- because I'm

00:08:34.429 --> 00:08:37.539
a vegan person who's
semi in the spotlight,

00:08:37.539 --> 00:08:40.630
I really want to show people,
look, you can feel great,

00:08:40.630 --> 00:08:43.190
and be really healthy,
and have a balanced diet,

00:08:43.190 --> 00:08:46.240
and be out there kicking
ass on a vegan diet.

00:08:46.240 --> 00:08:50.160
So I don't want to
be way overweight

00:08:50.160 --> 00:08:51.370
and not feeling incredible.

00:08:51.370 --> 00:08:55.740
But yeah, any kind of potato
product, french fries,

00:08:55.740 --> 00:08:56.240
samosas--

00:08:56.240 --> 00:08:57.490
MALE SPEAKER: So French fries?

00:08:57.490 --> 00:08:59.740
ADAM SOBEL: Yeah, I mean
exactly what I've set out

00:08:59.740 --> 00:09:02.500
to not have my wife eating.

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:03.180
She's right.

00:09:03.180 --> 00:09:04.629
Pirogis are dope.

00:09:04.629 --> 00:09:05.420
Don't get me wrong.

00:09:05.420 --> 00:09:07.770
There's a good pirogi
recipe in the book too.

00:09:07.770 --> 00:09:10.720
There's a truffled
pirogi recipe.

00:09:10.720 --> 00:09:14.670
That's my Achilles Heel.

00:09:14.670 --> 00:09:17.710
MALE SPEAKER: So
why then did you

00:09:17.710 --> 00:09:20.810
decide to pursue a food
truck instead of a more

00:09:20.810 --> 00:09:22.490
traditional restaurant?

00:09:22.490 --> 00:09:24.955
ADAM SOBEL: So after the
first restaurant where

00:09:24.955 --> 00:09:29.190
I'd been working, which was
not a vegetarian restaurant--

00:09:29.190 --> 00:09:31.560
I started working in all
these vegetarian and vegan

00:09:31.560 --> 00:09:39.060
restaurants-- I always felt
like the clientele was largely

00:09:39.060 --> 00:09:44.210
people who were already
vegan or accepting of it.

00:09:44.210 --> 00:09:47.430
And I felt like culturally
we have such a stigma

00:09:47.430 --> 00:09:49.420
against vegan and
vegetarian food,

00:09:49.420 --> 00:09:52.270
partially because it was
terrible in the '80s and '90s

00:09:52.270 --> 00:09:54.730
what most people experienced.

00:09:54.730 --> 00:09:57.830
You know, like
macrobiotic-y type food,

00:09:57.830 --> 00:10:01.970
and then there was this era
of very, very processed vegan

00:10:01.970 --> 00:10:05.720
food, all the fake
meat made in Taiwan.

00:10:05.720 --> 00:10:08.150
It's just two
extremes that were not

00:10:08.150 --> 00:10:12.650
very good that became the
public's consensus of what

00:10:12.650 --> 00:10:14.530
vegan food was about.

00:10:14.530 --> 00:10:18.230
And I really wanted to be
able to bring vegan food out

00:10:18.230 --> 00:10:21.780
into the world where people
who would never be caught dead

00:10:21.780 --> 00:10:24.600
going to a vegan restaurant
would see this huge, long line

00:10:24.600 --> 00:10:25.440
down the street.

00:10:25.440 --> 00:10:27.190
And there's this display
case of all these

00:10:27.190 --> 00:10:29.300
really tempting
looking doughnuts.

00:10:29.300 --> 00:10:32.180
And they'd be like lured
into the dark side.

00:10:32.180 --> 00:10:35.775
So that was always
my intention with it.

00:10:35.775 --> 00:10:38.760
And in my experience,
that's really

00:10:38.760 --> 00:10:41.850
what we accomplished with it.

00:10:41.850 --> 00:10:44.870
I think, predominantly,
we served

00:10:44.870 --> 00:10:48.700
people who really didn't
give a shit about veganism

00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:51.785
and were just excited that
it was really yummy food

00:10:51.785 --> 00:10:54.370
and available to them right
in front of their office.

00:10:54.370 --> 00:10:59.820
And to me, that's the
biggest part of our success.

00:10:59.820 --> 00:11:02.830
It's that we've
been able to help

00:11:02.830 --> 00:11:05.820
dispel some people's
misconceptions about it

00:11:05.820 --> 00:11:07.257
as a culinary form.

00:11:07.257 --> 00:11:08.090
MALE SPEAKER: I see.

00:11:08.090 --> 00:11:11.870
So it was bringing food out
on the street to the masses,

00:11:11.870 --> 00:11:14.820
like the street food that
you like in Southeast Asia

00:11:14.820 --> 00:11:16.335
and in that same vein.

00:11:22.860 --> 00:11:26.090
Suppose I wanted to
open a food truck.

00:11:26.090 --> 00:11:30.070
What should I expect in
terms of what's ahead for me?

00:11:30.070 --> 00:11:33.430
I mean, there's this perception
maybe that opening a food truck

00:11:33.430 --> 00:11:35.930
is easy whereas opening a
restaurant is difficult.

00:11:35.930 --> 00:11:36.680
ADAM SOBEL: Right.

00:11:36.680 --> 00:11:40.900
So for years, I would
get a couple people

00:11:40.900 --> 00:11:45.230
calling me or emailing me a week
asking me for advice about them

00:11:45.230 --> 00:11:47.110
opening a food truck.

00:11:47.110 --> 00:11:48.730
And I used to be
all like, aw yeah.

00:11:48.730 --> 00:11:49.610
You should go do it.

00:11:49.610 --> 00:11:52.980
It's the most fun
thing you ever did.

00:11:52.980 --> 00:11:54.020
It's so gratifying.

00:11:54.020 --> 00:11:56.290
People come up to
you all day, and they

00:11:56.290 --> 00:11:58.077
get really, really
happy in front of you,

00:11:58.077 --> 00:11:58.910
and then they leave.

00:11:58.910 --> 00:12:02.310
And it's really fun
in that capacity.

00:12:02.310 --> 00:12:08.170
But it's kind of the ultimate
food service nightmare too.

00:12:08.170 --> 00:12:11.720
It's every problem
that a restaurant has,

00:12:11.720 --> 00:12:15.600
because especially in the kind
of complex way we did our food,

00:12:15.600 --> 00:12:18.280
we had to have a huge
kitchen facility where

00:12:18.280 --> 00:12:19.990
we prepped everything at also.

00:12:19.990 --> 00:12:22.450
So we have all the
same different types

00:12:22.450 --> 00:12:25.219
of things break, all the
same kind of staffing issues

00:12:25.219 --> 00:12:25.760
and problems.

00:12:25.760 --> 00:12:27.530
MALE SPEAKER: How many people
worked behind the scenes there?

00:12:27.530 --> 00:12:28.860
ADAM SOBEL: Quite
a lot of people.

00:12:28.860 --> 00:12:29.410
MALE SPEAKER: A lot.

00:12:29.410 --> 00:12:31.368
ADAM SOBEL: By the time
we had a couple trucks,

00:12:31.368 --> 00:12:33.860
there was dozens of people.

00:12:33.860 --> 00:12:37.150
I mean, it's not [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:37.150 --> 00:12:40.760
We gave them Razor scooters
to get around the kitchen.

00:12:40.760 --> 00:12:41.385
But it wasn't--

00:12:41.385 --> 00:12:42.760
MALE SPEAKER: You
started with two people.

00:12:42.760 --> 00:12:44.093
ADAM SOBEL: It wasn't this dope.

00:12:48.240 --> 00:12:52.990
But yeah, it's extremely
prone to disaster.

00:12:52.990 --> 00:12:55.320
In addition to all the
things restaurants deal with,

00:12:55.320 --> 00:12:59.570
then there's you breaking down,
and there's parking tickets,

00:12:59.570 --> 00:13:03.640
and people have this really
confrontational thing

00:13:03.640 --> 00:13:04.460
with food trucks.

00:13:04.460 --> 00:13:06.450
Like, the pizza
place up the block

00:13:06.450 --> 00:13:09.330
feels like you're
unfair competition,

00:13:09.330 --> 00:13:11.110
and they'll call
the police on you.

00:13:11.110 --> 00:13:14.450
And then especially
in New York City,

00:13:14.450 --> 00:13:17.860
the laws are very different
city to city, but in New York,

00:13:17.860 --> 00:13:19.880
it's ridiculous.

00:13:19.880 --> 00:13:22.290
Essentially, food
trucks are more or less

00:13:22.290 --> 00:13:24.610
illegal in the city.

00:13:24.610 --> 00:13:28.300
There's this illegal black
market, which is the only way

00:13:28.300 --> 00:13:30.600
to obtain the permits for them.

00:13:30.600 --> 00:13:33.670
And then once you even get all
the permits, and insurance,

00:13:33.670 --> 00:13:35.600
and everybody's
got workers' comp,

00:13:35.600 --> 00:13:39.060
and everything's as legit
as you can possibly make it,

00:13:39.060 --> 00:13:40.800
they've made it
as of a few years

00:13:40.800 --> 00:13:46.590
ago so that you're not legally
even allowed to serve food

00:13:46.590 --> 00:13:48.570
if you're at a metered
location, which

00:13:48.570 --> 00:13:51.900
is every single commercial
space in Manhattan.

00:13:51.900 --> 00:13:55.080
So you could be in
a busy lunch rush,

00:13:55.080 --> 00:13:57.130
and police just come
and say you guys

00:13:57.130 --> 00:13:59.200
aren't allowed to operate
in front of a meter.

00:13:59.200 --> 00:14:00.180
You've got to go.

00:14:00.180 --> 00:14:05.250
So yeah, it's like every
nightmare of a restaurant

00:14:05.250 --> 00:14:07.310
but multiplied.

00:14:07.310 --> 00:14:11.730
It became almost like a
joke between me and my wife.

00:14:11.730 --> 00:14:16.960
Every day, there's always
some absurd thing happening.

00:14:16.960 --> 00:14:17.690
It's fun.

00:14:17.690 --> 00:14:19.330
And for me, it was
really worth it

00:14:19.330 --> 00:14:21.610
because I was
motivated by trying

00:14:21.610 --> 00:14:23.470
to change our
culture a little bit

00:14:23.470 --> 00:14:26.490
and trying to get the mainstream
to think a little bit more

00:14:26.490 --> 00:14:27.340
compassionately.

00:14:27.340 --> 00:14:31.640
So as far as I'm concerned,
enduring all these

00:14:31.640 --> 00:14:34.270
like hurdles and
issues, it's sort

00:14:34.270 --> 00:14:37.010
of a matter of life and
death for the animals

00:14:37.010 --> 00:14:39.820
who people ended up not eating.

00:14:39.820 --> 00:14:42.070
So it was very, very worth it.

00:14:42.070 --> 00:14:44.340
But yeah, most
people who just want

00:14:44.340 --> 00:14:46.990
to run whatever
kind of-- they want

00:14:46.990 --> 00:14:51.030
to do a waffle truck because
it's trendy right now.

00:14:51.030 --> 00:14:54.620
Now I just tell them you could
save yourself so many headaches

00:14:54.620 --> 00:14:57.830
by doing it as a restaurant
and not a food truck.

00:14:57.830 --> 00:15:02.920
MALE SPEAKER: So you mentioned
this shady black market

00:15:02.920 --> 00:15:05.107
of permitting.

00:15:05.107 --> 00:15:06.190
So I'm curious about this.

00:15:06.190 --> 00:15:08.500
Without implicating
me, making me

00:15:08.500 --> 00:15:11.030
a conspirator in any
way, what can you tell me

00:15:11.030 --> 00:15:15.050
about these shady permits that
people-- not you, I'm sure--

00:15:15.050 --> 00:15:16.430
are acquiring out there.

00:15:16.430 --> 00:15:17.180
ADAM SOBEL: Right.

00:15:17.180 --> 00:15:22.000
So yeah, as of the early
'80s in New York City,

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:26.530
this cap was placed on the
number of vending permits

00:15:26.530 --> 00:15:30.640
both for trucks and carts
it's the same permit.

00:15:30.640 --> 00:15:35.490
And when they went in
place, anyone who had them

00:15:35.490 --> 00:15:37.420
was able to keep
renewing them for about

00:15:37.420 --> 00:15:39.160
the cost of $100 a year.

00:15:39.160 --> 00:15:42.450
So they realized now
there's this heavy demand

00:15:42.450 --> 00:15:45.340
for these permits, and they
can keep holding on to them

00:15:45.340 --> 00:15:48.930
and renewing them and
renting them out illegally

00:15:48.930 --> 00:15:55.180
from more than 100 times
what they look they're worth.

00:15:55.180 --> 00:15:56.720
And there's no other way.

00:15:56.720 --> 00:15:59.290
You can't get on a waiting
list because nobody's

00:15:59.290 --> 00:16:02.190
going to let theirs expiring
go back into the system.

00:16:02.190 --> 00:16:04.920
So it's amazing in
New York City, which

00:16:04.920 --> 00:16:08.960
you feel is like hyper
controlled environment

00:16:08.960 --> 00:16:11.410
where there's police everywhere.

00:16:11.410 --> 00:16:16.910
But still so many things are
regulated in this shady fashion

00:16:16.910 --> 00:16:17.940
in New York.

00:16:17.940 --> 00:16:20.820
It's the same for
taxicab medallions,

00:16:20.820 --> 00:16:25.340
and liquor licenses, and
a variety of other things.

00:16:25.340 --> 00:16:29.030
So that actually prevented
us from opening up initially

00:16:29.030 --> 00:16:32.880
in New York City because we
just couldn't even find one.

00:16:32.880 --> 00:16:36.180
It took a couple years before
we are able to obtain one,

00:16:36.180 --> 00:16:40.060
and it was the shadiest thing
I've ever had to deal with.

00:16:40.060 --> 00:16:42.764
I bought drugs when I was a kid
on the street in New York City.

00:16:42.764 --> 00:16:46.600
This was way, way
more shady than that.

00:16:46.600 --> 00:16:49.450
And it's large sums
of money in cash

00:16:49.450 --> 00:16:53.240
you're handling some guy in
an industrial area of Queens

00:16:53.240 --> 00:16:54.665
in a paper bag.

00:16:54.665 --> 00:16:55.910
It's horrendous.

00:16:55.910 --> 00:16:58.345
I don't recommend having to
do that to run your business.

00:16:58.345 --> 00:17:00.825
MALE SPEAKER: That's exactly
out of the movies basically.

00:17:00.825 --> 00:17:01.550
ADAM SOBEL: Yeah.

00:17:01.550 --> 00:17:06.630
I regularly had to deal with the
cast of the Sopranos and stuff.

00:17:06.630 --> 00:17:10.569
MALE SPEAKER: So while we're
on the subject of bureaucracy,

00:17:10.569 --> 00:17:13.905
what are the health regulations
and health inspections

00:17:13.905 --> 00:17:14.780
like for food trucks?

00:17:14.780 --> 00:17:16.279
Are they different
from restaurants?

00:17:16.279 --> 00:17:18.829
ADAM SOBEL: Yeah, actually
it's another really big

00:17:18.829 --> 00:17:21.970
misconception people
have about food trucks.

00:17:21.970 --> 00:17:25.920
Because I guess 20
or 30 years ago,

00:17:25.920 --> 00:17:32.340
they were this completely
unregulated outlaw thing.

00:17:32.340 --> 00:17:38.220
I mean, now a food truck gets
way more meticulously health

00:17:38.220 --> 00:17:40.112
inspected and way
more frequently

00:17:40.112 --> 00:17:42.320
because they're going to
all different neighborhoods.

00:17:42.320 --> 00:17:48.000
So they'll jump on the
truck at your busiest time

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:51.630
ever and be looking with a
flashlight at the underside

00:17:51.630 --> 00:17:55.070
of the corner of the
counters for any--

00:17:55.070 --> 00:17:58.510
it's really very difficult.

00:17:58.510 --> 00:18:01.280
So food trucks really have
to be up on their game

00:18:01.280 --> 00:18:04.050
because the fines are enormous.

00:18:04.050 --> 00:18:06.040
And they can shut
you down completely.

00:18:06.040 --> 00:18:08.580
So just like a restaurant
has, food trucks

00:18:08.580 --> 00:18:11.970
have to have all the same
working hand washing facilities

00:18:11.970 --> 00:18:16.940
and all this type of stuff,
which is a huge challenge.

00:18:16.940 --> 00:18:20.280
Your restaurant parks outside in
the winter, and all your pipes

00:18:20.280 --> 00:18:22.160
want to freeze
every night, and it

00:18:22.160 --> 00:18:24.920
becomes this whole
other dimension of crap

00:18:24.920 --> 00:18:29.040
to have to worry about to be
able to be up to health code.

00:18:29.040 --> 00:18:30.980
But it's doable.

00:18:30.980 --> 00:18:31.857
It's just hard.

00:18:31.857 --> 00:18:32.690
MALE SPEAKER: I see.

00:18:32.690 --> 00:18:35.440
So it seems like the
bureaucrats, the policemen,

00:18:35.440 --> 00:18:38.760
they can either be your best
friend or your worst nightmare.

00:18:38.760 --> 00:18:42.820
In "Street Vegan," you
tell an interesting story

00:18:42.820 --> 00:18:44.880
about an experience
you had in Hoboken

00:18:44.880 --> 00:18:48.261
with a police officer
who gave you a hard time.

00:18:48.261 --> 00:18:49.260
Can you talk about that?

00:18:49.260 --> 00:18:49.968
ADAM SOBEL: Sure.

00:18:49.968 --> 00:18:53.850
So Hoboken, like I was saying,
all the towns and cities

00:18:53.850 --> 00:18:59.140
have their own unique
ordinances about vending.

00:18:59.140 --> 00:19:01.340
And Hoboken's one
was really weird.

00:19:01.340 --> 00:19:05.730
It was that you had
to move your food

00:19:05.730 --> 00:19:09.250
truck after every single sale.

00:19:09.250 --> 00:19:12.280
You know in the suburbs, like
the roving ice cream trucks?

00:19:12.280 --> 00:19:16.620
They'll throw you an ice cream
out the window type of thing?

00:19:16.620 --> 00:19:20.930
It can only work for
pre-packaged junk food type

00:19:20.930 --> 00:19:21.790
products, you know?

00:19:21.790 --> 00:19:25.120
If you're setting up an official
kitchen on the street, that

00:19:25.120 --> 00:19:29.030
takes at least 45 minutes
to just get everything

00:19:29.030 --> 00:19:32.890
settled, and the grills
lit, and all this stuff.

00:19:32.890 --> 00:19:36.190
So like it is in
New York where you

00:19:36.190 --> 00:19:38.620
have to find this
balance of where to park,

00:19:38.620 --> 00:19:40.880
where nobody's going to
call the police on you,

00:19:40.880 --> 00:19:43.250
and these types of
things, in Hoboken, it

00:19:43.250 --> 00:19:48.730
was like you had to find a
spot where you could stay,

00:19:48.730 --> 00:19:50.490
and had good enough
foot traffic,

00:19:50.490 --> 00:19:53.190
and nobody was going to
bother you-- somewhere

00:19:53.190 --> 00:19:55.570
on the outskirts of town.

00:19:55.570 --> 00:19:57.590
MALE SPEAKER: Where you
might do a cash deal.

00:19:57.590 --> 00:20:02.240
ADAM SOBEL: Yeah, it was very
typical of food truck world.

00:20:02.240 --> 00:20:06.580
So in the first week or
two I was operating, still

00:20:06.580 --> 00:20:10.230
really learning the ropes of
how all this stuff worked.

00:20:10.230 --> 00:20:16.380
We opened on Valentine's Day of
2010, and it was freezing cold.

00:20:16.380 --> 00:20:19.000
The first day we were
shoveling feet of snow

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:21.980
off the roof of our truck
when we were opening.

00:20:21.980 --> 00:20:26.866
And it was so slow on
this one waterfront block

00:20:26.866 --> 00:20:28.740
that I had found that
was kind of safe that I

00:20:28.740 --> 00:20:33.190
started venturing deeper into
the downtown area of Hoboken.

00:20:33.190 --> 00:20:38.000
And this one morning I set up,
and after making a couple sales

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:44.130
this cop came in
full Gestapo leather.

00:20:44.130 --> 00:20:47.982
He's the policeman from
hell type of character.

00:20:47.982 --> 00:20:48.940
And he's like, oh yeah.

00:20:48.940 --> 00:20:50.720
You've got to move right now.

00:20:50.720 --> 00:20:53.720
So it was early on
a Sunday morning.

00:20:53.720 --> 00:20:57.010
I saw there was a spot across
the block, so I went over there

00:20:57.010 --> 00:20:58.010
and I opened up.

00:20:58.010 --> 00:21:01.070
And I sold somebody
in order of pancakes,

00:21:01.070 --> 00:21:02.580
and immediately
the guy was back.

00:21:02.580 --> 00:21:06.490
He was like, I'm going to keep
following you around all today.

00:21:06.490 --> 00:21:08.370
You gotta keep moving.

00:21:08.370 --> 00:21:12.600
And I didn't really get it.

00:21:12.600 --> 00:21:16.410
And I was packing up slowly so
he came back and immediately

00:21:16.410 --> 00:21:18.950
issued me $500 in tickets.

00:21:22.050 --> 00:21:26.680
He made it clear he was going
to just make my day hell.

00:21:26.680 --> 00:21:31.480
And I had a whole truck full
of freshly made doughnuts

00:21:31.480 --> 00:21:34.630
and all this stuff that was
just going to go to waste.

00:21:34.630 --> 00:21:39.880
And I knew I had to just pack
up for the day at that point.

00:21:39.880 --> 00:21:43.790
And thinking about it,
just driving out of town

00:21:43.790 --> 00:21:45.325
I stopped at the
police precinct.

00:21:45.325 --> 00:21:46.560
And I was like, OK.

00:21:46.560 --> 00:21:49.950
Here's all the doughnuts
I have, you guys.

00:21:49.950 --> 00:21:53.090
I don't even know what to
expect tomorrow when I come back

00:21:53.090 --> 00:21:56.850
to operate in this town.

00:21:56.850 --> 00:22:02.610
And I came back the next
day, and I felt bad.

00:22:02.610 --> 00:22:06.140
The guy had been so mad
at me, this policeman.

00:22:06.140 --> 00:22:10.580
So I went to the police
station and I asked for him

00:22:10.580 --> 00:22:12.990
by name, the police officer.

00:22:12.990 --> 00:22:14.360
And I introduced myself.

00:22:14.360 --> 00:22:15.240
And I was like, look.

00:22:15.240 --> 00:22:17.430
I'm really not
trying to be a dick.

00:22:17.430 --> 00:22:21.464
I just want to make
vegetarian food for people.

00:22:21.464 --> 00:22:25.470
And immediately just because
I had talked to him about it,

00:22:25.470 --> 00:22:26.610
he was a little bit nicer.

00:22:26.610 --> 00:22:30.250
And a week later, I was serving
again food on the waterfront

00:22:30.250 --> 00:22:33.910
and I saw this
police car pull up.

00:22:33.910 --> 00:22:37.355
And I'm on the phone with my
wife because it's real slow.

00:22:37.355 --> 00:22:38.990
And I'm like, oh shit.

00:22:38.990 --> 00:22:40.410
The police are here.

00:22:40.410 --> 00:22:41.530
I've gotta go.

00:22:41.530 --> 00:22:42.860
And it's the policeman.

00:22:42.860 --> 00:22:45.150
He comes out, and he
orders all this food.

00:22:45.150 --> 00:22:47.980
And there's a couple
people waiting on food.

00:22:47.980 --> 00:22:50.440
And he's giving
them rave reviews,

00:22:50.440 --> 00:22:53.290
telling them which
doughnuts to get.

00:22:53.290 --> 00:22:55.420
He started bringing
other cops there,

00:22:55.420 --> 00:22:59.000
and they'd get tofu
sandwiches and stuff.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:02.990
So yeah, if you're ever harassed
by the police, it's true.

00:23:02.990 --> 00:23:07.242
You just have to feed them
truckloads of doughnuts

00:23:07.242 --> 00:23:08.670
and it fixes all your problems.

00:23:08.670 --> 00:23:09.030
MALE SPEAKER: Wow.

00:23:09.030 --> 00:23:10.071
And that just works, huh?

00:23:10.071 --> 00:23:11.590
ADAM SOBEL: Yeah.

00:23:11.590 --> 00:23:13.750
MALE SPEAKER: So I guess
speaking of the food,

00:23:13.750 --> 00:23:16.100
let's start talking more
about the food instead

00:23:16.100 --> 00:23:19.940
of the bureaucracy, as
interesting as all that is.

00:23:19.940 --> 00:23:23.130
You mentioned how every
once and a while, you'll

00:23:23.130 --> 00:23:26.560
have to throw out a meal that
you made that's just no good.

00:23:26.560 --> 00:23:28.890
You're constantly
experimenting with dishes

00:23:28.890 --> 00:23:30.370
and that sort of stuff.

00:23:30.370 --> 00:23:33.644
What are your current
most exciting experiments?

00:23:33.644 --> 00:23:34.810
Can't you share any with us?

00:23:34.810 --> 00:23:38.305
Or do they stay top secret
until they see the light of day?

00:23:38.305 --> 00:23:38.930
ADAM SOBEL: No.

00:23:38.930 --> 00:23:40.680
I mean, there's so much stuff.

00:23:40.680 --> 00:23:42.920
I'm always experimenting,
especially at home

00:23:42.920 --> 00:23:45.480
with my wife who does
a lot of pastry stuff.

00:23:45.480 --> 00:23:50.815
So we're constantly tweaking
and perfecting new things.

00:23:50.815 --> 00:23:53.270
And there are
things too that I'll

00:23:53.270 --> 00:23:56.050
come to be great at
making, and I always

00:23:56.050 --> 00:23:57.710
feel like I can
get better at it.

00:23:57.710 --> 00:24:00.730
I mean, a perfect example
are the doughnuts we make,

00:24:00.730 --> 00:24:04.010
which there's a very
comprehensive chapter

00:24:04.010 --> 00:24:06.670
for in the book.

00:24:06.670 --> 00:24:08.700
It's something
that I'm constantly

00:24:08.700 --> 00:24:11.860
playing with and tweaking
different methods

00:24:11.860 --> 00:24:13.920
for exactly how they're glazed.

00:24:13.920 --> 00:24:17.290
And if you glaze the doughnuts
while the doughnuts themselves

00:24:17.290 --> 00:24:19.480
are still warm, it has
a very different effect

00:24:19.480 --> 00:24:21.690
than if you glaze
them after they've

00:24:21.690 --> 00:24:24.290
cooled, because the
warmth of the doughnut

00:24:24.290 --> 00:24:27.725
makes the glaze drip
down in a thinner way.

00:24:27.725 --> 00:24:30.110
And there's constantly
stuff like that.

00:24:30.110 --> 00:24:33.790
Another thing which you guys
had in the cafeteria today

00:24:33.790 --> 00:24:36.050
are the [? bo ?]
buns, which there's

00:24:36.050 --> 00:24:38.210
a few recipes for in the book.

00:24:38.210 --> 00:24:40.820
It's like a Chinese
style steam bun.

00:24:40.820 --> 00:24:44.060
And I'm really tweaking
the method I do that with,

00:24:44.060 --> 00:24:48.840
because I have this great idea
about doing vegan hamburgers

00:24:48.840 --> 00:24:52.330
on Chinese style steam buttons.

00:24:52.330 --> 00:24:54.870
So to make it work out
as a real burger bun

00:24:54.870 --> 00:24:58.020
it takes some tweaking so
that's still soft and wonderful

00:24:58.020 --> 00:24:59.360
but can be substantial.

00:25:02.820 --> 00:25:05.690
MALE SPEAKER: So
I'd imagine that one

00:25:05.690 --> 00:25:08.401
of the challenges for this
book is taking recipes

00:25:08.401 --> 00:25:10.400
that you normally make
for hundreds of thousands

00:25:10.400 --> 00:25:14.480
and making it so that I can
make five at home or something

00:25:14.480 --> 00:25:15.560
like that.

00:25:15.560 --> 00:25:17.560
What was the process you
went through in terms

00:25:17.560 --> 00:25:21.870
of picking recipes and then
coming up with measurements

00:25:21.870 --> 00:25:23.170
that a home cook could follow?

00:25:23.170 --> 00:25:25.690
And how do you know that the
recipes come out good in a home

00:25:25.690 --> 00:25:26.440
kitchen?

00:25:26.440 --> 00:25:28.530
ADAM SOBEL: Yeah.

00:25:28.530 --> 00:25:31.130
Really, all the
recipes had to be

00:25:31.130 --> 00:25:33.070
recreated from the ground up.

00:25:33.070 --> 00:25:37.750
We do them in such large volumes
and use industrial equipment

00:25:37.750 --> 00:25:41.890
for making them that it
really only made sense

00:25:41.890 --> 00:25:45.420
to figure out instead of
doing the math of dividing

00:25:45.420 --> 00:25:51.005
the recipe we have by
2000, figuring it out fresh

00:25:51.005 --> 00:25:54.370
and really approximating
the taste perfectly.

00:25:54.370 --> 00:25:59.060
And then I had a great
collection of different recipe

00:25:59.060 --> 00:26:00.290
testers I worked with.

00:26:00.290 --> 00:26:04.180
And I really tried to have
both people who are really

00:26:04.180 --> 00:26:07.420
novice cooks and people who
were more professional so

00:26:07.420 --> 00:26:10.290
that the people who
really knew about cooking

00:26:10.290 --> 00:26:12.430
could point out the
stupid mistakes I've made,

00:26:12.430 --> 00:26:15.550
and the people who were
terrible at cooking

00:26:15.550 --> 00:26:17.350
would ask me the
dumb questions that I

00:26:17.350 --> 00:26:19.400
assumed people might know.

00:26:19.400 --> 00:26:21.550
So that really helped
me hone things.

00:26:21.550 --> 00:26:25.460
But the thing about doing the
book for me that was really fun

00:26:25.460 --> 00:26:27.850
is that on the truck
itself we're really

00:26:27.850 --> 00:26:31.110
limited in the kind of equipment
we have for serving food.

00:26:31.110 --> 00:26:34.950
We really just have a flat
top griddle on the truck.

00:26:34.950 --> 00:26:36.750
So doing the book
really allowed me

00:26:36.750 --> 00:26:41.390
to start having recipes
available to people for things

00:26:41.390 --> 00:26:44.380
that I wish we could offer--
dumplings on the truck,

00:26:44.380 --> 00:26:47.710
and there's all these really
hooked up entrees in the truck

00:26:47.710 --> 00:26:49.090
as well.

00:26:49.090 --> 00:26:50.727
So that was really
a fun opportunity.

00:26:50.727 --> 00:26:52.560
MALE SPEAKER: So there's
recipes in the book

00:26:52.560 --> 00:26:54.113
that people have
never seen if they've

00:26:54.113 --> 00:26:55.130
been to the Cinnamon Snail?

00:26:55.130 --> 00:26:56.004
ADAM SOBEL: For sure.

00:26:56.004 --> 00:26:58.100
Some of it are things
that we've always

00:26:58.100 --> 00:27:01.300
offered for catering and stuff.

00:27:01.300 --> 00:27:03.410
The entrees, it's kind of funny.

00:27:03.410 --> 00:27:05.910
A lot of them we did used
to have on the truck.

00:27:05.910 --> 00:27:08.840
Because when I first
opened the truck,

00:27:08.840 --> 00:27:11.030
I thought it'd be
this great idea

00:27:11.030 --> 00:27:14.780
to not have any sandwiches
whatsoever on our truck, which

00:27:14.780 --> 00:27:17.500
has become synonymous
with what we do.

00:27:17.500 --> 00:27:21.560
But I just wanted to have all
these architectural, beautiful

00:27:21.560 --> 00:27:25.430
entrees all stacked up with
beautiful fried garnishes

00:27:25.430 --> 00:27:26.960
on them and stuff.

00:27:26.960 --> 00:27:30.620
And so when I opened, I had
like 13 different entrees

00:27:30.620 --> 00:27:33.290
on the truck and maybe like
a sandwich or something.

00:27:33.290 --> 00:27:38.830
And it's a completely
absurd impractical idea

00:27:38.830 --> 00:27:41.130
I had that people
would be willing to eat

00:27:41.130 --> 00:27:46.360
that on a paper plate in their
lap during their lunch time.

00:27:46.360 --> 00:27:49.680
So that's why the food
we do on the truck

00:27:49.680 --> 00:27:52.910
gravitated so much towards
it being like almost a whole

00:27:52.910 --> 00:27:55.220
entree in between
two pieces of bread.

00:27:55.220 --> 00:27:57.350
Some of the things
we serve on the truck

00:27:57.350 --> 00:28:00.450
are really complex like that.

00:28:00.450 --> 00:28:03.740
MALE SPEAKER: And so you have
some very complex recipes.

00:28:03.740 --> 00:28:07.430
And in the book, you helpfully
go through all the ingredients

00:28:07.430 --> 00:28:11.450
you'll see later in the
book and what they are.

00:28:11.450 --> 00:28:12.970
So there are a lot
of ingredients,

00:28:12.970 --> 00:28:15.500
and some folks here,
especially in Manhattan,

00:28:15.500 --> 00:28:17.230
don't have gigantic kitchens.

00:28:17.230 --> 00:28:20.830
What are the must haves
for a good vegan kitchen?

00:28:20.830 --> 00:28:23.177
ADAM SOBEL: Well, I mean,
I guess everybody's tastes

00:28:23.177 --> 00:28:23.760
are different.

00:28:23.760 --> 00:28:27.590
But definitely one
of my desert island,

00:28:27.590 --> 00:28:30.680
I get to bring one
seasoning ingredient with me

00:28:30.680 --> 00:28:35.340
to the desert island, is plum
vinegar, the umeboshi plum

00:28:35.340 --> 00:28:36.290
vinegar.

00:28:36.290 --> 00:28:39.540
It's kind of in an
embarrassing number of things

00:28:39.540 --> 00:28:42.170
I make because I
love it so much.

00:28:42.170 --> 00:28:44.890
It really has this
very bright umame kind

00:28:44.890 --> 00:28:46.790
of salty, tangy flavor.

00:28:46.790 --> 00:28:51.040
You would think plum vinegar
sounds so sweet and fruity,

00:28:51.040 --> 00:28:56.700
but it's this really tangy--
really brings things to life.

00:28:56.700 --> 00:28:59.660
It's great in all kinds of
dressings, and marinades,

00:28:59.660 --> 00:29:01.170
and sauces.

00:29:01.170 --> 00:29:03.820
I use it even in soups.

00:29:03.820 --> 00:29:07.550
But yeah, it's really
a great seasoning.

00:29:07.550 --> 00:29:09.027
That's definitely
one of my go-to.

00:29:09.027 --> 00:29:11.110
MALE SPEAKER: That's a
must have for your kitchen?

00:29:11.110 --> 00:29:14.060
ADAM SOBEL: Yeah, I mean,
there are so many things

00:29:14.060 --> 00:29:19.360
that we use on the truck
that we rely on it,

00:29:19.360 --> 00:29:23.690
and it allows us to do a very
simple preparation with it

00:29:23.690 --> 00:29:24.510
that's versatile.

00:29:24.510 --> 00:29:27.570
So for instance in the book,
which we use on the truck,

00:29:27.570 --> 00:29:30.640
there's a recipe for just
very simply marinaded

00:29:30.640 --> 00:29:33.690
kale that is just
massaged with plum

00:29:33.690 --> 00:29:36.680
vinegar and extra virgin
olive oil, some black pepper,

00:29:36.680 --> 00:29:38.010
and thyme.

00:29:38.010 --> 00:29:40.840
And it's a very simple,
easy to make recipe,

00:29:40.840 --> 00:29:44.050
and it makes the greens
really easily digestible

00:29:44.050 --> 00:29:46.520
because the acidity
of the vinegar

00:29:46.520 --> 00:29:49.340
penetrates the cells of the
greens and makes it soft,

00:29:49.340 --> 00:29:51.540
almost like sauteed greens.

00:29:51.540 --> 00:29:55.680
But it doesn't impart a very
specific flavor profile on it,

00:29:55.680 --> 00:29:59.770
so we'll use that
same marinaded kale

00:29:59.770 --> 00:30:04.280
in a variety of different
things on the truck.

00:30:04.280 --> 00:30:06.490
It's in our Korean
barbecue seitan,

00:30:06.490 --> 00:30:09.250
and it's also on the
Thanksgiving style sandwich

00:30:09.250 --> 00:30:09.750
