00:30:25.030 --> 00:30:28.290
are dishes that people probably
don't know how to make vegan

00:30:28.290 --> 00:30:31.240
or that non-vegans
are surprised to taste

00:30:31.240 --> 00:30:33.570
and there's no animal
products in them.

00:30:33.570 --> 00:30:37.280
So how do you veganize pastries?

00:30:37.280 --> 00:30:39.070
Is it all your wife?

00:30:39.070 --> 00:30:41.315
Has she got the secret
recipes for that?

00:30:41.315 --> 00:30:45.410
ADAM SOBEL: She is magical,
but it's taken a lot of us

00:30:45.410 --> 00:30:48.430
both tweaking the recipes.

00:30:48.430 --> 00:30:50.730
And I mean, to be
honest, I think

00:30:50.730 --> 00:30:52.880
most people wouldn't
know how to make a not

00:30:52.880 --> 00:30:54.220
vegan doughnut either.

00:30:54.220 --> 00:30:57.580
It's not something that
a lot of people do.

00:30:57.580 --> 00:31:02.370
And to be honest,
it's a pastry art form

00:31:02.370 --> 00:31:06.760
that I feel was
almost completely lost

00:31:06.760 --> 00:31:10.290
during the '70s
through the '90s.

00:31:10.290 --> 00:31:15.380
Really, this industrialized
model of doughnut production

00:31:15.380 --> 00:31:18.200
started proliferating,
stuff like Krispy Kreme,

00:31:18.200 --> 00:31:22.190
and Dunkin' Donuts,
and Tim Horton's.

00:31:22.190 --> 00:31:26.770
And really, the
kind of mom and pop

00:31:26.770 --> 00:31:30.270
handmade doughnut tradition
was almost completely

00:31:30.270 --> 00:31:34.410
lost because it was something as
a culinary form that was never

00:31:34.410 --> 00:31:36.040
really very well documented.

00:31:36.040 --> 00:31:38.660
There's only a
couple very-- I mean,

00:31:38.660 --> 00:31:41.100
there's not many books about it.

00:31:41.100 --> 00:31:44.220
Most resources online
about doughnut making start

00:31:44.220 --> 00:31:49.920
with a can of Pillsbury
muffin mix or whatever.

00:31:49.920 --> 00:31:53.640
And it's something that
learning to do vegan,

00:31:53.640 --> 00:31:56.000
we really had to
start with nothing

00:31:56.000 --> 00:31:59.910
and just start making
stuff up and trying things.

00:31:59.910 --> 00:32:03.690
And writing a doughnut
chapter for the book

00:32:03.690 --> 00:32:05.562
was a really
interesting challenge

00:32:05.562 --> 00:32:07.520
because it's not the type
of thing you can just

00:32:07.520 --> 00:32:11.560
hand somebody a recipe for
and expect them to pull it off

00:32:11.560 --> 00:32:12.260
with finesse.

00:32:12.260 --> 00:32:15.710
There's kind of a
lot of variables that

00:32:15.710 --> 00:32:17.642
can really make or break it.

00:32:17.642 --> 00:32:19.990
We created these
doughnut recipes,

00:32:19.990 --> 00:32:23.060
and that we would figure one
day would come out amazing,

00:32:23.060 --> 00:32:24.650
and the next day
they'd be horrible

00:32:24.650 --> 00:32:27.150
and had soaked up all this oil.

00:32:27.150 --> 00:32:31.610
And we would start noticing
the exact amount of time

00:32:31.610 --> 00:32:36.230
that the doughnut sit before
you actually form them

00:32:36.230 --> 00:32:39.770
into doughnuts, the dough sits
so that the liquids really

00:32:39.770 --> 00:32:42.230
hydrate the cells of the flour.

00:32:42.230 --> 00:32:43.820
It really matters.

00:32:43.820 --> 00:32:46.270
And you know exactly
how frequently

00:32:46.270 --> 00:32:48.420
you filter the oil if
you're frying doughnuts

00:32:48.420 --> 00:32:54.790
every day if you're not
throwing out the entire $700

00:32:54.790 --> 00:32:58.740
fryer worth of
doughnut oil every day.

00:32:58.740 --> 00:33:02.380
You have to filter it very
frequently because the oil

00:33:02.380 --> 00:33:04.230
starts transforming.

00:33:04.230 --> 00:33:07.570
So in writing that
chapter, I had

00:33:07.570 --> 00:33:11.110
to lay down a little
bit of a primer

00:33:11.110 --> 00:33:14.210
on exactly some of
those variables,

00:33:14.210 --> 00:33:17.295
exactly how long you want
to mix the dough for,

00:33:17.295 --> 00:33:19.990
and how to proof the
doughnuts if you don't have

00:33:19.990 --> 00:33:22.620
a commercial proofing oven.

00:33:22.620 --> 00:33:24.840
So yeah, it forced me
to get really creative

00:33:24.840 --> 00:33:27.020
and think of all these things.

