00:40:29.750 --> 00:40:31.310
a lobbying technique for you?

00:40:31.310 --> 00:40:34.600
ADAM SOBEL: Well, if it's
pizza guys I'm up against,

00:40:34.600 --> 00:40:36.140
they already eat
mad dough products.

00:40:36.140 --> 00:40:37.990
MALE SPEAKER: I say go straight
to the straight to the mayor

00:40:37.990 --> 00:40:38.630
though.

00:40:38.630 --> 00:40:40.870
I mean, ultimately,
the Two Boots guy--

00:40:40.870 --> 00:40:44.000
ADAM SOBEL: You know, the
problem is for food trucks

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:47.020
that no matter where
we operate, there's

00:40:47.020 --> 00:40:50.960
always many forms of
opposition to face.

00:40:50.960 --> 00:40:53.590
And all over the
country, there's

00:40:53.590 --> 00:40:56.360
been these food truck
coalitions starting up.

00:40:56.360 --> 00:40:59.660
In New York City, there's
the Street Vendor Project

00:40:59.660 --> 00:41:01.860
and the New York City
Food Truck Association,

00:41:01.860 --> 00:41:04.160
which both try to fight
for vendors' rights.

00:41:04.160 --> 00:41:08.350
But we're the smallest
type of small businesses

00:41:08.350 --> 00:41:10.680
versus every
Starbucks in New York

00:41:10.680 --> 00:41:14.331
City who has lobbying
power and all this stuff.

00:41:14.331 --> 00:41:16.080
AUDIENCE: I wonder if,
