ADAM SOBEL: Aww!

00:41:53.590 --> 00:41:55.970
AUDIENCE: I tried to start
eating vegan three years ago.

00:41:55.970 --> 00:41:59.540
I had very serious health
issues that I couldn't get over,

00:41:59.540 --> 00:42:01.480
and switching to
vegan really fixed it.

00:42:01.480 --> 00:42:03.870
And the first time
I had Cinnamon Snail

00:42:03.870 --> 00:42:07.319
in Jersey City, that was
when I switched from saying

00:42:07.319 --> 00:42:09.860
"eating vegan really sucks, but
it's making me healthy so I'm

00:42:09.860 --> 00:42:12.351
going to do it" to "this
is freaking awesome.

00:42:12.351 --> 00:42:14.100
I've never had anything
like this before."

00:42:14.100 --> 00:42:17.670
So thanks so much for doing that
and then also bringing it here

00:42:17.670 --> 00:42:19.709
to work after the
truck went away,

00:42:19.709 --> 00:42:22.250
which was the most depressing
time in my time in Jersey City.

00:42:24.997 --> 00:42:26.580
I wanted to tell you
that so you know.

00:42:26.580 --> 00:42:30.570
But what I really wanted to
ask about is the word vegan.

00:42:30.570 --> 00:42:32.860
I feel like there's
such a stigma associated

00:42:32.860 --> 00:42:35.650
with the word for really
no good reason, right?

00:42:35.650 --> 00:42:37.530
I mentioned that
your food is here

00:42:37.530 --> 00:42:41.980
today to some of my colleagues,
and that it's really, really

00:42:41.980 --> 00:42:44.740
amazing and they should take
the trip to the 8th floor

00:42:44.740 --> 00:42:46.990
make it happen.

00:42:46.990 --> 00:42:51.430
And they said, yeah, I'm a
meat and potatoes kind of guy.

00:42:51.430 --> 00:42:53.100
I'm not that adventurous.

00:42:53.100 --> 00:42:55.010
And there's really
nothing adventurous

00:42:55.010 --> 00:42:57.310
about not eating
animal products,

00:42:57.310 --> 00:43:00.830
like having some vegetables or
tofu or something like that.

00:43:00.830 --> 00:43:03.980
But that's the attitude
about the word vegan.

00:43:03.980 --> 00:43:07.990
And before I became vegan
or start eating vegan food,

00:43:07.990 --> 00:43:10.227
my mother-in-law used
that word all the time.

00:43:10.227 --> 00:43:12.560
And as somebody who was not
someone who ate in that way,

00:43:12.560 --> 00:43:13.643
I found it very offensive.

00:43:13.643 --> 00:43:15.350
Like, you think
you're better than me?

00:43:15.350 --> 00:43:16.590
You make vegan food?

00:43:16.590 --> 00:43:18.360
You're some fancy vegan?

00:43:18.360 --> 00:43:21.800
I'm just wondering that given
that it has such a stigma,

00:43:21.800 --> 00:43:24.630
and vegetarian has much less of
a stigma because it sounds more

00:43:24.630 --> 00:43:28.110
like the word
vegetable, I guess,

00:43:28.110 --> 00:43:30.640
is there a way to
maybe-- I think

00:43:30.640 --> 00:43:33.710
there is a movement towards more
people believing that the vegan

00:43:33.710 --> 00:43:36.720
eating is a more sustainable
way to run the planet

00:43:36.720 --> 00:43:39.210
and it's healthier for people
and people generally like it,

00:43:39.210 --> 00:43:42.170
but people also generally
dislike the word.

00:43:42.170 --> 00:43:44.590
I wonder if there's a way to
come up with a new marketing

00:43:44.590 --> 00:43:49.770
campaign like "eat for
life" or "pro-animal."

00:43:49.770 --> 00:43:52.440
ADAM SOBEL: Yeah, I mean, people
are calling it plant-based.

00:43:52.440 --> 00:43:55.420
There's all these different
words that have been coined.

00:43:55.420 --> 00:43:58.080
But I mean, I think
what our culture

00:43:58.080 --> 00:44:04.390
is dealing with is more
deeply psychological, right?

00:44:07.240 --> 00:44:09.430
The excuse that people
are afraid that's

00:44:09.430 --> 00:44:12.020
not going to be yummy or that
it's not going to make them

00:44:12.020 --> 00:44:14.490
feel great-- there's all
these different excuses,

00:44:14.490 --> 00:44:21.700
but I think more
fundamentally it's

00:44:21.700 --> 00:44:27.410
because it's an ethical
attempt to really try to limit

00:44:27.410 --> 00:44:29.970
the violence we cause, right?

00:44:29.970 --> 00:44:33.030
It forces people
to observe the way

00:44:33.030 --> 00:44:37.300
they've lived their whole life
and that's very painful when

00:44:37.300 --> 00:44:39.380
you realize you've been
living in such a way

00:44:39.380 --> 00:44:42.820
your whole life
that's indirectly

00:44:42.820 --> 00:44:44.370
caused a lot of suffering.

00:44:44.370 --> 00:44:46.690
And it's something
that a lot of people

00:44:46.690 --> 00:44:50.410
would rather keep out of
sight and out of mind.

00:44:50.410 --> 00:44:54.480
So people get really
defensive about it

00:44:54.480 --> 00:44:58.470
and will become very
offensive towards veganism

00:44:58.470 --> 00:45:03.390
because it challenges
their moral ideology.

00:45:03.390 --> 00:45:05.660
Not to get real
philosophical about it,

00:45:05.660 --> 00:45:08.790
but I think that's a really
big part of our culture's

00:45:08.790 --> 00:45:11.430
opposition towards
it, not to say

00:45:11.430 --> 00:45:13.860
that it's even a perfect
model in and of itself.

00:45:13.860 --> 00:45:15.940
I mean, there's a
lot of varieties

00:45:15.940 --> 00:45:18.870
of ways people can eat
in a vegan way that are

00:45:18.870 --> 00:45:22.210
more or less nonviolent, right?

00:45:22.210 --> 00:45:25.010
But I think that's really
what a lot of folks

00:45:25.010 --> 00:45:26.250
struggle with about it.

00:45:26.250 --> 00:45:29.320
I don't think it needs to
be marketed differently.

00:45:29.320 --> 00:45:32.220
I think our culture
just needs to take

00:45:32.220 --> 00:45:36.430
a little more time with it
before it really can accept it

00:45:36.430 --> 00:45:38.240
and comprehended
it in its fullest.

00:45:38.240 --> 00:45:38.702
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:45:38.702 --> 00:45:39.326
Thanks so much.

00:45:41.936 --> 00:45:42.649
ADAM SOBEL: Hey.

00:45:42.649 --> 00:45:43.440
AUDIENCE: Hi, Adam.

00:45:43.440 --> 00:45:45.522
Thank you so much for coming.

00:45:45.522 --> 00:45:48.950
I have one and a half questions.

