This is yerba mate.

00:45:57.400 --> 00:46:03.720
It's a tea from
Argentina and Uruguay.

00:46:03.720 --> 00:46:06.210
The straw is called
a bombilla, which

00:46:06.210 --> 00:46:08.260
has this strainer at
the bottom, and it's

00:46:08.260 --> 00:46:11.400
a lot of very thick herbs.

00:46:11.400 --> 00:46:14.730
It's really tasty,
in my opinion,

00:46:14.730 --> 00:46:17.570
but it's one of these things
that people love or hate.

00:46:17.570 --> 00:46:19.760
It's almost got a
tobacco-y quality

00:46:19.760 --> 00:46:24.240
in some weird way, a very
all around your mouth palette

00:46:24.240 --> 00:46:25.870
experience.

00:46:25.870 --> 00:46:29.800
But it's sort of great for you.

00:46:29.800 --> 00:46:32.290
I think it's probably
like 90% what

00:46:32.290 --> 00:46:35.940
I'm made out of because
I consume a lot of it.

00:46:35.940 --> 00:46:38.640
But yeah, it's like a
multivitamin in some ways.

00:46:38.640 --> 00:46:41.080
It's got a ton of amino
acids and minerals,

00:46:41.080 --> 00:46:43.561
lots of B vitamins, magnesium.

00:46:43.561 --> 00:46:44.310
That's what it is.

00:46:44.310 --> 00:46:45.435
AUDIENCE: That's very cool.

00:46:45.435 --> 00:46:46.660
I like tea a lot.

00:46:46.660 --> 00:46:50.320
My actual question is I'm
curious where the name Cinnamon

00:46:50.320 --> 00:46:52.410
Snail originated.

00:46:52.410 --> 00:46:55.890
ADAM SOBEL: Well, I get
asked this question a lot,

00:46:55.890 --> 00:46:59.190
and honestly, I wish I
had a cooler background

00:46:59.190 --> 00:47:01.335
story because then I
would have this cool story

00:47:01.335 --> 00:47:02.210
to tell all the time.

00:47:02.210 --> 00:47:05.110
But really it just sounds cute.

00:47:05.110 --> 00:47:08.200
It's another name for cinnamon
buns, which my wife and I were

00:47:08.200 --> 00:47:10.800
making for our local
farmers' market

00:47:10.800 --> 00:47:12.860
before we launched the truck.

00:47:12.860 --> 00:47:19.210
And really the
translation in Danish,

00:47:19.210 --> 00:47:21.970
I believe it's
kanelsnegle, is what

00:47:21.970 --> 00:47:23.980
you call a cinnamon
bun, which directly

00:47:23.980 --> 00:47:26.380
translates to cinnamon snail.

00:47:26.380 --> 00:47:32.247
But yeah, really it
just sounds cute.

00:47:32.247 --> 00:47:33.080
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:47:33.080 --> 00:47:34.930
ADAM SOBEL: Yeah.

00:47:34.930 --> 00:47:35.430
Hey.

00:47:35.430 --> 00:47:36.013
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:47:36.013 --> 00:47:37.450
Thanks so much for coming.

00:47:37.450 --> 00:47:40.460
I one time stopped
by the Cinnamon Snail

00:47:40.460 --> 00:47:43.440
immediately before a bus
back home to Virginia.

00:47:43.440 --> 00:47:45.660
And now my folks expect
a donut every time

00:47:45.660 --> 00:47:47.690
I come back so
you've really helped

00:47:47.690 --> 00:47:52.210
me raise the expectations
for me as a son.

00:47:52.210 --> 00:47:54.290
So I have a question.

00:47:54.290 --> 00:47:56.860
There's a part that's of
personal interest to me,

00:47:56.860 --> 00:47:59.400
and then something that other
people might find interesting.

00:47:59.400 --> 00:48:02.050
My landlord shut off my
gas like a month ago,

00:48:02.050 --> 00:48:05.090
and there's no word on
when that's coming back.

00:48:05.090 --> 00:48:08.230
And so I guess the more
microquestion is do you

00:48:08.230 --> 00:48:11.160
have any good recipes that only
use a slow cooker and a rice

00:48:11.160 --> 00:48:11.660
cooker?

00:48:14.360 --> 00:48:17.880
ADAM SOBEL: What you need to
get is an induction burner,

00:48:17.880 --> 00:48:19.700
like an electric
induction burner.

00:48:19.700 --> 00:48:23.192
Then you could cook a
lot of things with that.

00:48:23.192 --> 00:48:29.590
Yeah, there's not too many Easy
Bake Oven recipes in my book.

00:48:29.590 --> 00:48:31.420
Yeah, get yourself
an induction burner.

00:48:31.420 --> 00:48:33.120
But get your
landlord in trouble.

00:48:33.120 --> 00:48:33.850
That's not right.

00:48:33.850 --> 00:48:35.141
You gotta get some gas back on.

00:48:35.141 --> 00:48:36.830
AUDIENCE: I'm working on it.

00:48:36.830 --> 00:48:39.060
OK, and then I guess my
more interesting question

00:48:39.060 --> 00:48:41.760
is sort of related to that.

00:48:41.760 --> 00:48:44.610
I take it that
cooking in the truck

00:48:44.610 --> 00:48:46.590
and then cooking in
like a real kitchen--

00:48:46.590 --> 00:48:49.170
not that your truck doesn't
have a real kitchen,

00:48:49.170 --> 00:48:52.280
but a more traditional
kitchen is very different.

00:48:52.280 --> 00:48:54.720
And do you find that the
constrained environment

00:48:54.720 --> 00:48:59.050
of the truck has led you to be
more creative with your recipes

00:48:59.050 --> 00:49:00.710
in any way?

00:49:00.710 --> 00:49:03.650
ADAM SOBEL: That's an
interesting question.

00:49:03.650 --> 00:49:06.450
Well, the format of
the truck and the fact

00:49:06.450 --> 00:49:10.070
that we became this
astronomically busy food

00:49:10.070 --> 00:49:13.680
truck that has-- it's
a very limited space

00:49:13.680 --> 00:49:18.640
you have in a truck, and you can
only fit so many people in it

00:49:18.640 --> 00:49:20.510
to be preparing the food.

00:49:20.510 --> 00:49:24.990
So more than anything what it
really causing me to rethink

00:49:24.990 --> 00:49:27.770
is ways we could prepare
this food as quickly

00:49:27.770 --> 00:49:32.440
as humanly possible without it
diminishing from the complexity

00:49:32.440 --> 00:49:35.680
and the freshness of it.

00:49:35.680 --> 00:49:38.380
I don't know how much that's
reflected in the book,

00:49:38.380 --> 00:49:42.960
because the book doesn't
have those same constraints.

00:49:42.960 --> 00:49:49.270
But what it did is force
me to also plan ways

00:49:49.270 --> 00:49:52.040
we could prepare the different
components of the food

00:49:52.040 --> 00:49:55.410
so it was really just the very
quick reheating and assembly

00:49:55.410 --> 00:49:57.460
of things on the truck.

00:49:57.460 --> 00:50:02.440
We have this 5,000 square foot
production kitchen in Brooklyn

00:50:02.440 --> 00:50:05.940
where we make all the different
sauces and things like that.

00:50:05.940 --> 00:50:08.280
But yeah, it was a
really fun challenge,

00:50:08.280 --> 00:50:11.240
and that's something
that's really always been

00:50:11.240 --> 00:50:15.870
attractive to me
creatively-- forcing myself

00:50:15.870 --> 00:50:21.380
to deal with these irrational
types of challenges as a cook

00:50:21.380 --> 00:50:24.620
or in any creative capacity.

00:50:24.620 --> 00:50:27.120
That's one of the things
that's been fun for me to learn

00:50:27.120 --> 00:50:29.757
how to make vegan food like.

00:50:29.757 --> 00:50:31.340
At first, it almost
seemed like you're

00:50:31.340 --> 00:50:33.730
cooking with one hand
tied behind your back.

00:50:33.730 --> 00:50:36.880
And then how you're
going to prepare food

00:50:36.880 --> 00:50:39.350
for some guest who
comes who's paleo

00:50:39.350 --> 00:50:41.130
and you want it to be vegan too.

00:50:41.130 --> 00:50:42.480
I love that type of stuff.

00:50:42.480 --> 00:50:44.930
Or be on some show
and you've gotta

00:50:44.930 --> 00:50:47.930
